Conduct detailed engineering assessments before preparing POWs and ensure that project plans are tailored to the specific needs; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly apply the prescribed recording standards on receipts and consumption/distribution of inventories and follow the perpetual inventory method of recording inventories.

To avoid the penalties for non-compliance with certain provisions of RA No. 9003, we recommended that Management:
Convert its controlled dump into a sanitary landfill with minimum provisions for liners, leachate treatment, gas control, groundwater monitoring system, and covers;
Allocate sufficient funds for the establishment of an MRF and for the operation of the Biodegradable Waste Shredder and Composter to maximize the use of these equipment;
Enforce the mandatory segregation policy in garbage collection and transport and impose appropriate fines for violation thereof; and
Provide protective gear to all garbage collectors to protect them from prolonged exposure to waste and garbage.

We recommended that:
Management submits a written explanation for the full payment made to the contractor despite non-completion of the foregoing projects;
Require the contractor to rectify the deviations from approved plans and specifications identified by the DILG, particularly the undersized pipes;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to verify the accuracy of details provided in the SWA before certifying it; and
Mandate the Municipal Accountant to include the Aide Memoire as a prerequisite before facilitating full payment of projects funded by LGSF-SBDP to ensure that the total amount claimed and paid corresponds with the actual accomplishment of the project.
An inspectorate team be constituted to inspect projects to ensure that claims on progress billings for infrastructure projects will be technically and thoroughly validated to protect the interest of the public.

We recommended that the Management issue instructions to the Executive Committee and Technical Working Group to undertake the following actions:
Ensure judicious and prudent utilization of GAD funds;
Implement all programmed GAD PPAs and, if necessary, adopt appropriate remedial measures to ensure the complete execution of the entire GAD PPAs, thereby maximizing the achievement of desired results;
Stop the practice of granting unauthorized additional incentives to its employees; and
Conduct a post-assessment evaluation of the implemented GAD PPAs to determine their effectiveness and success. This evaluation should also identify emerging gender issues to ensure that the needs for gender equality and women empowerment are continuously addressed and updated.

We recommended that the Management:
