cause the refund of the bonuses and incentive amounting to P67,864.00;

stop the grant of benefits and incentive to the COS personnel to avoid the incurrence of irregular disbursements;

strictly adhere to the rules and regulations governing the grant of such benefits and incentive otherwise, continuous payment thereof will be disallowed.

We recommended that Management:

direct the offices in-charge in the implementation of LGU projects; the Municipal Engineer or the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to prepare the ObR of LGU projects specifically those charged against the 20% EDF;

require the OIC- Municipal Budget Officer to closely monitor the status of allotments, obligations and disbursements in consonance with Section 4.5 of the Budget Operations Manual of LGUs and reconcile records with the Accounting Office at the end of each month; 

require the General Service Office to closely coordinate with the end-users/implementing units on the preparation and submission of required documents to support the obligation of projects; 

strictly comply with Sections 4.5 and 5.6 of the Budget Operations Manual for LGUs and Section 2.0 of COA Circular 2006-002 dated January 31, 2006; and

require the OIC- Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to rectify their reports in the obligation of funds of the contracts/projects subject of this observation.

We recommended the following:
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) to direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of physical inventory and render report thereon as required under Section 124, Chapter 7, Volume I of the NGAS Manual.  The progress of the inventory taking should be monitored by the LCE;
Thereafter, the Committee, the GSO and the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) reconcile all the inventory reports with the books of accounts;
Require the designated Property Officer to maintain property cards and update them periodically to aid in the conduct of physical count and to solve or minimize the perennial problem of unreconciled Accounting and Property records; and
Require the previous Chairmen of the Inventory Committee to explain their failure to completely conduct inventory and render report thereon. Likewise, the Committee should be warned that failure to perform their duties as Chairman and Members of the Inventory Committee may be a valid ground for filing of administrative charges for gross neglect of duty.

We recommended that the management faithfully comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 77-61 to effectively control fuel by implementing the following corrective measures:
Exercise tighter control over the use of government vehicles through the completion of duly approved serially numbered DTTs and RIVs;
Management submit to the AT the Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Report of Official Travels for audit and verification purposes.

1.	Require the Finance Committee, Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer to review the unexpended balances and unobligated appropriations of PPAs carried over as CY 2019 Continuing Appropriations to determine which are eligible as continuing PPAs pursuant to the provisions of Sections 321 and 322 of RA No, 7160.

2.	After reviewing the unexpended PPAs, consider the following courses of actions:

a.	Revert the unobligated/unexpended appropriation of PPAs which are no longer to be pursued by the agency;

b.	Require the MDC to revisit the unfunded priority projects in the development plan or propose new projects for re-appropriation from the unappropriated surplus;

c.	Request the SB to pass appropriation ordinance related thereto, and once approved, execute without delay the projects.

We recommended that the Local School Board Council:

prioritize the implementation of projects that will address the deficiency of school facilities and instruction materials, and;

coordinate with the respective DepEd officials regarding budget for security services and other maintenance and operating expenses that should be shouldered by DepED rather than the Municipality.

We recommended the following:
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) reorganize the Inventory Committee and require the same to conduct physical inventory and render report thereon as required under Section 124, Chapter 7, Volume I of the NGAS Manual. The progress of the inventory taking should be monitored by the Local Chief Executive;
Thereafter, the Committee, the General Services Office and the Municipal Accounting Office reconcile all the inventory reports with the books of accounts;
Require the designated Property Officer to maintain property cards and update them periodically to aid in the conduct of physical count and to solve or minimize the perennial problem of unreconciled Accounting and Property records; and
Require the previous Chairmen of the Inventory Committee to explain their failure to conduct inventory and render report thereon. Likewise, the Committee should be warned that failure to perform their duties as Chairman and Members of the Inventory Committee may be a valid ground for filing of administrative charges for gross neglect of duty.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
Designated GSO to consolidate the weekly RIS  in the SSMI for CY 2019 and previous years transactions, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant together with the original copies of RIS;
Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary JEVs based on the submitted SSMIs and record the expenditures under the Prior Period Adjustment account pursuant to Section 121 of NGAS Manual, Volume I.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Finance Committee, Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer to review the unexpended balances and unobligated appropriations of PPAs carried over as CY 2019 Continuing Appropriations to determine which are eligible as continuing PPAs pursuant to the provisions of Sections 321 and 322 of RA No, 7160.
After reviewing the unexpended PPAs, consider the following courses of actions:
Revert the unobligated/unexpended appropriation of PPAs which are no longer  to be pursued by the agency;
Require the MDC to revisit the unfunded priority projects in the development plan or propose new projects for re-appropriation from the unappropriated surplus;
Request the SB to pass appropriation ordinance related thereto, and once approved, execute without delay the projects.

We recommended that the Municipal Engineer:
Conduct an inventory of local roads implemented in prior years, including the identification of each component and submit a report thereon to the Municipal Accountant for reconciliation with those recorded in the books; and
Identify the road projects that should be turned-over to the barangays, based on the recorded projects in the books of the Municipal Accountant.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Transfer the cost of the Barangay road projects to the books of the Barangay concerned;
Record the municipal roads and its components based on the appraisal of the Municipal Engineer;
Maintain property ledger cards for each public infrastructure for proper monitoring of transactions;
Prepare a lapsing schedule to compute depreciation of each infrastructure asset, and;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify the projects erroneously recorded as Road Networks to the appropriate account.
We further reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Treasurer, as the Designated General Services Officer, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Require the Human Resource and Management Officer to assess the existing Organizational Structure of the LGU to determine the possibility of hiring qualified persons for the vacant plantilla positions and submit a report with recommendations to the LCE;
Create policies and guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring JOs taking into consideration the existing regular employees;
Limit the hiring of personnel under Job Order contracts to those extremely necessary and state in the JO contracts the specific offices that are actually in need of their services;
Require Job Orders to submit primary personal identification, undergo interview and evaluate the performance of each to provide assurance that only qualified persons are hired by the LGU;
Specify in the JO’s contract the number of man hours required, quantity and duration of the work to be performed by the JO personnel and require each JO to submit quantified accomplishment reports to support payments of wages; and
Discontinue hiring individuals who are 65 years old and above.

We recommended that: The Municipal Accountant:

Reconcile the book balance of Road Network account with the Inventory Report;

Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for roads and its components to support the Road Network account.

The Municipal Engineer:

Conduct an inventory of local roads implemented in prior years, including the identification of each component and submit a report thereon to the Municipal Accountant for reconciliation with those recorded in the books;

Prepare a Road Map and provide a copy to the Property Officer.

The Municipal Treasurer as the Property Officer:

Maintain a Local Road Inventory;

Maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components as prescribed in Annex E of the said Circular.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

determine the acquisition dates of the assets in the Infrastructure Asset account and;

compute the depreciation expense of each in order to present the proper carrying value of said assets.

We recommend that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

Limit the hiring of Job Order Workers only to the most necessary to avoid redundant assignments with permanent personnel and reduce maintenance and operating expenses, and;

Give the JOs the mandated daily minimum wage at rates prescribed by the Regional Tripartite Wages and Productivity Boards for Region VIII .

We recommended the following courses of action to the Management:
The General Services Officer to consolidate the weekly RIS   in the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) for CY 2015 and previous years transactions, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant together with the original copies of RIS;
The Municipal Accountant to compute the cost of supplies/inventories issued based on the SSMI and prepare the JEV to record the expenditure using the appropriate expenditure accounts pursuant to Section 121 of NGAS Manual, Volume I.

We recommended that Management:

a. suspend the salaries of erring accountable officers until such time that full settlement of their cash advances are effected;

b.  require all officials and employees who are still in service to refund in full their outstanding cash advances;

c stop the practice of granting cash advances to officials and employees unless the previous ones are fully liquidated;

d. see to it that officials and employees who seek transfer to other offices or those filing for terminal leaves are not given certificates of clearance until their balances are paid; and

e. ensure that rules and regulations on the grant of cash advances are strictly observed.

We recommended that Management: a. instruct ~ the Inventory Committee to prepare and provide all the information needed in the RPCPPE as well as certify the same and submit a copy to COA within the prescribed period;

b.  require the . General Services Officer/Property Officer to reconcile the property records of each class of PPE with the accounting records, investigate the differences and adjustments be effected immediately; and

c.  direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated PPE ledger cards to support GL account balances and the GSO to keep corresponding property cards for control purposes. These records should contain adequate details/description of the properties such as model, serial number, location, cost and other information necessary to facilitate its identification.
